Research question: How are NBA players’ salaries determined? What can it tell us about the player?¶

1 Introduction¶

In 2020, Netflix released “The Last Dance”, a 10 episode sports documentary retracing the career of Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls as they attempt to win the NBA championship in the 1997-1998 season. The locker room footage shown in this documentary allowed viewers to gain privileged access to the backstage of a fascinating journey. It also uncovered the convoluted human relations between the members of the bulls organisation. In particular, the open conflict between Scottie Pipen (Small Forward for the Bulls from 1987 to 1998) (Basketball Reference) and the back office of the organisations was featured in length. With 11 siblings and a disabled father depending on him, Scottie Pippen chose security when he signed a 6 year renewable contract with the Chicago Bulls. This agreement soon turned out to be a costly mistake for the young player as his salary did not match his talents nor his importance on the Chicago Bulls’ roster. As Michael Jordan’s right arm and the second most valuable player in the best team of the league, Scottie Pipen only ranked as the 6th highest paid player on the team and the 122nd in the league(Quinn, 2020). This allowed Jerry Krause, the general manager of the Bulls, to build a superteam around his two star players and win 6 championships in 11 years, a feat yet to be reproduced since.

Between 2011 and 2018, the league’s revenue swoll from 3.68 to 8.76 billion dollars (138%) and the average NBA salary rose by 55%(Statista, 2022). The overwhelming success of “The Last Dance” shed a light on this growing popularity and underlined the importance of wage management in the success of a basketball team. In fact, salaries have become such a central topic in the modern NBA, that some tend to forget that human beings lie behind these million dollar contracts. Henceforth, we decided to conduct an analysis on NBA salaries in an effort to understand what they can tell us about basketball players.

1.1 A special market¶

In order to ensure that the game of basketball remains exciting for fans and challenging for players, the NBA strives to level the playing field for every team in the league. For instance, the fairness of competition is enforced by the draft system, where the worst standing teams of the regular season get the first draft picks (a lottery where every young player debuting in the league is assigned to a team). Unlike workers in the free market economy, the salaries of NBA players are capped. Essentially, the NBA puts a soft cap on salary expenditure per season so as to ensure fairness between all teams in the league. Indeed, teams with bigger markets, superior historical achievements or higher external funding would have an unfair advantage in the recruitment of talents as they would be able to offer more attractive salaries to prospects and free agents. To combat that, the league reduces their privileges in the free agency and imposes heavy taxes if a team exhibits total salary costs superior to the salary cap and luxury tax cap (both are calculated as a % of the leagues revenue in the last season) (Coon, 2011). This effectively renders it impossible to maintain a squad with a total salary that far exceeds the league’s limits. Player salary is one of the most important operating costs for an NBA team and it is interesting to see how NBA salaries evolved under these particular conditions. Indeed, even though the basketball association imposes an upper limit on total team salary, no limit is put on individual player salaries which can lead to high discrepancies between teammates.

Being a team sport, the overall success of a team results from the sum of every player’s contribution to the overall performance of the team. However, unlike in many other professions, the performance of NBA players is highly monitored and can hence be analysed. It is hard to gauge how much a single McDonald's employee contributes to the overall success of the restaurant as most of his actions are not quantified (an exact record of burgers made or tables wiped does not exist), or quantifiable (smiling to a client or helping a struggling colleague for instance). In basketball however, stats are plentiful and they can be used to quantify the exact contribution of every player on a given team. The idea behind our salary analysis is hence to reveal the principal determinants of salary and unveil the potential biases or discriminations hidden in the league. To do so, we will analyse and correlate player performance, experience, nationality and position with their salaries. Furthermore, we will execute a time series analysis from 2007 to 2017 in order to comprehend the evolution of player salaries and its distribution across time.

1.2 Literature review¶

As Michael Lewis explained in the movie Moneyball, “People in both fields operate with beliefs and biases. To the extent you can eliminate both and replace them with data, you gain a clear advantage.” Whether in industry or in sports, rigorous data analysis has become indispensable to inform decisions in high performing organisations. It is hence not surprising that the biggest basketball league became a subject of study for data scientists around the world. In his essay titled “Modelling the labour markets of the NBA”, Deepan Modi uses the Markowitz Model to analyse the allocation of salary in the NBA. This method enables him to measure a player’s value relative to his teammates and helps to identify underpaid prospects. On average, he found that 5.4 players are underpaid in every NBA team. The leading cause of this misalignment is hypothesised to be the artificial constraints imposed by the salary cap on the labour market. Then, Tyler Matthew Stanek in his paper “Player Performance and Team Revenues: NBA Player Salary Analysis” found that, judging by player performance, veterans were generally overpaid at the expense of young players. Once again, it is hypothesised that NBA rules such as the “veterans minimum” is responsible for the visible distortion in the labour market. Furthermore, Stanek finds that general managers put an overemphasis on points scored when analysing player performance. This shows the embedded biases of managers when distributing salaries within teams.

2 The Data¶

2.1 Introducing the data¶

For this project, we will be using data from the most complete online statistique library in American Sports: Stathead Basketball. This website records thousands of box score statistiques on historical basketball games and players from the NBA. Unfortunately, no API existed for the data we were interested in. We chose to focus our analysis on the 2016-17 season, as it is the latest season that was neither riddled with scandals nor affected by the COVID-19 pandemic. Later, we webscrapped 10 additional seasons to perform a time series analysis from 2007 to 2017.

2.2 Obtaining the data¶

For our analysis, we started by web scraping the box score of every player in the 2016-17 season. This table was composed of 486 players and 29 columns containing various information on them. From this table, we kept 5 variables containing their name, team, position, age and the link to their individual player page. Using an iteration process, we then web scraped each of the individual player pages with the links collected, and collected more personal information including their salary (for 2017), experience (years in the league), and Player Efficiency Rating (PER). After some cleaning, we merged this data into a single data frame containing 484 players and 9 variables. Two players, Tim Quarterman and Kyle Wiltjer, were dropped as no salary information was available for them.

As seen from the box plot and violin plot, the distribution of salaries in 2017 was positively skewed. This can be explained by the fact that the majority of players earned between 0 and 5 million dollars that season. In fact the 4th quartile of the boxplot is a lot longer than the preceding three, which indicates a bigger variability of salaries in that part of the distribution. Furthermore, the presence of a long tail in the violin plot hints at an unequal repartition of salaries in the NBA. Hence, it seems that 8 figure salaries are the exception in the league and that most players can hope to earn around \$3.2 million (that is the median of the salaries that season). Furthermore, it can be hypothesised that a handful of players were paid a large proportion of their team’s salary cap this season. This pushed the average salary of NBA players up such that the mean salary was \\$6.15 million that season (nearly twice as much as the median). In fact, the gini coefficient of NBA salaries in 2017 was 0.55 (see Lorenz curve below). As a comparaison, Mozambique, Ezwatini and the central African Republic have gini coefficients similar to that of the NBA. This suggests that NBA salaries are approximately as unequally distributed as the wealth of people in some of the most unequal countries of the world.

## Obtaining gini-coefficient of salaries

x = data['Salary']
x = x.values.tolist()
v = np.array(x)

def G(v):
    bins = np.linspace(0, 100, 11)
    total = float(np.sum(v))
    yvals = []
    for b in bins:
        bin_vals = v[v <= np.percentile(v, b)]
        bin_fraction = (np.sum(bin_vals) / total) * 100.0
        yvals.append(bin_fraction)
    # Perfect equality area
    pe_area = np.trapz(bins, x=bins)
    # Lorenz area
    lorenz_area = np.trapz(yvals, x=bins)
    gini_val = (pe_area - lorenz_area) / float(pe_area)
    return bins, yvals, gini_val
gini = G(v)
gini = gini[-1]
print("The gini coefficient is: " + str(gini))

3 What affects salary?¶

3.1 Performance and experience¶

To uncover the reason behind such an unequal distribution of salaries, we wondered if salaries are a good indicator of how experienced and performant NBA players are. The hypothesis is that the more experienced and performant a player is, the more valuable he is to his team and hence the higher salary he can expect to receive.

To evaluate the performance of NBA players fairly, we decided to use performance efficiency ratings. In John Hollinger’s (inventor of the PER) own words, "The PER sums up all a player's positive accomplishments, subtracts the negative accomplishments, and returns a per-minute rating of a player's performance".

For more information on the formula for calculating PER, please visit: https://www.basketball-reference.com/about/per.html.

# Grouping years of experience
def categorize_exp(exp):
    if exp <= 3:
        exp_group = '01-03'
    elif exp <= 6:
        exp_group = '04-06'
    elif exp <= 9:
        exp_group = '07-09'
    elif exp <= 10:
        exp_group = '10-12'
    elif exp <= 15:
        exp_group = '13-15' 
    elif exp <= 18:
        exp_group = '16-18'
    else:
        exp_group = '19-22'
    return exp_group

In this scatter plot (interactive version included as HTML file: ‘1scatterplot_perf_exp.html’), we can clearly see a correlation between performance and salary as well as between experience and salary. This comforts our hypothesis that the NBA rewards performance and experience.

There are also several extremely highly paid players observed, such as Lebron James, Russell Westbrook, Kevin Durant and James Harden located at the top right corner of the graph. Lebron James was the season’s highest earning player (close to \$31mil), though not the best performing. Westbrook is the season’s best performing (PER=30.6) and crowned the most valuable player, yet earned almost \\$5 million less. Clearly, there are other factors at play here, not all of which we can determine from the scatterplot. For one, experience could play a role as James accumulated a few more years of experience on the court than his peers.

Also, it is interesting to note that most of the players with high PER and low salary also have low experience. This might be explained by two factors. The first could be that these players signed short contracts and were not good enough to earn a real spot in a team’s roster. Their high PER would hence only be a fluke resulting from a small sample size. Alternatively, the salary limits put on “rookie contracts” signed by young players could explain why some players are underpaid. New players do not choose which team they join and hence have little bargaining power. Furthermore, the league strictly limits rookie contracts (salaries cannot exceed a % of the total salary cap of a franchise) which explains why some players like the 2021 MVP (Most Valuable Player) Nikola Jokic was so severely underpaid in 2017.

3.2 Do positions matter?¶

Next, we wondered if the roles played by NBA players on the court had an influence on their salaries.

The game of basketball is played with 10 players on the court. Naturally, this implies that each team relies on 5 players to rebound, pass, block, steal or score the ball. Like in the military, every player has a different role to play in order to make the team as efficient and performant as possible.

The roles are divided as follows:

  • Point Guard (The general): He is responsible for running the plays, organising the offence and making good passes. He is often smaller than his teammates but is an excellent dribbler.
  • Center (The tank): He is often the tallest player on the team, plays close to the basket and tries to get as many offensive and defensive rebounds as possible. On defence he is responsible for guarding the basket and blocking incoming shots.
  • Shooting Guard (The sniper): He is the team’s best shooter and can shoot the ball from behind the 3 point line. He is also a good dribbler and can create plays as well.
  • Small Forward (The Swiss knife): He can defend against all opposing players as well as score from close and long distance.
  • Power Forward (Support): His role is similar to the centers although he can shoot from further and is often more mobile.

We first visualise the same relationship between salary and PER, but coloured by positions instead (interactive version included as HTML file: ‘2scatterplot_perf_pos.html’). The rationale behind this decision is simple: the position an NBA player plays on court could have an effect on his PER and at the same time, could be an attribute that fetches higher or lower earnings, in other words certain positions could be positively favoured. Plotting both variables on the same graph against salary data could reveal patterns and correlations not just between the independent variable and the salary variable, but also between the two independent variables. From the scatterplot, it is difficult to discern a clear correlation between position and salary - no one position consistently fetched higher salaries than another. However, it does seem like centers tend to get higher PER scores, which could in turn result in them having higher salaries. In order to explore this potential confounding factor, we dive into how performance statistics differ between positions. First, we have to extract the performance statistics of all the players, sorted by positions. The second code chunk is a replication of the first, but with four other positions.

3.3 Domestic vs Foreign: Is there discrimination or favouritism?¶

While NBA basketball is watched and enjoyed by people in all corners of the world, it is largely dominated by US players. We obtained the birth countries of 484 players in the 2016-2017 and found that 368 of them were domestic players and only 116 were foreign players - over 75% of NBA players are Americans. However, there has been an increasing trend in the number of foreign-born NBA players (cite), with international representation reaching an all-time high of 25.1% in the previous season (cite). In fact, some of the biggest names in the NBA and crowned All-Star players are not from the US, including Giannis Antetokounmpo from Greece and Rudy Gobert from France. We thus wonder if domestic or foreign players suffer from wage discriminations because of their nationality. Does the NBA value foreign players more because of visibility and market acquisition? Or does the NBA favour domestic players because of protectionism or marketing?

The sankey diagram above shows the flow of salary by region. We first found out what the 30th and 70th percentile of salary was (\$2mil and \\$7mil respectively), then split the NBA players’ salaries into three bins: the bottom 30 percentile, the 30-70th percentile (average) and the top 30 percentile. There is no obvious bias in salary distribution with the given regions of the world. However, some observations can be made. Firstly, it is no surprise that the US players dominate all three bins as they make up the biggest group, but it is worth noting that the US players take up a bigger proportion in the bottom 30 percentile bin than they do in the other two. European players are slightly more likely to end up in the higher salary bins, as do players from the Middle East and Oceania, though the latter could be inaccurate due to the small sample size. Most of the South American players, on the other hand, end up in the lower salary bins. The small sample size makes it difficult to come to conclusions - certain players could all happen to come from the same region and end up earning more simply because they have really good skills and not because of where they come from. If the same analysis is done on a bigger sample size, perhaps including smaller leagues or other seasons, more conclusive remarks could be made. Nonetheless, for the season 2016-17, it seems unlikely that there has been any discrimination or favourtism towards foreign players.

3.4 Do some teams pay more than others?¶

The next natural question one could ask is whether salaries differ from team to team. More interestingly, one can wonder what salary distributions tell us about the profile of the league’s teams.

As we can see from these boxplots, salary distributions vary a lot in the NBA. Some teams like Orlando, Sacramento or Indiana seem to have well distributed wages. Indeed, their median salary is centred in the box plot and their distribution is only slightly skewed. More importantly, they have no outliers. This hints to the fact that these teams are built around a cast of good players but have no superstars taking up a big share of their salary space. On the other hand, teams like the Houston Rockets, the Atlanta Hawks or the Oklahoma Thunder seem to be built around one or a couple very expensive players. Indeed, their box plots either show many outliers or a long fourth quartile whisker. Salaries can henceforth inform us on the strategy of basketball teams. Some will rely on teamwork and pay relatively equal pay to their players while others will count on their superstars and build an accompanying cast of lower paid players around them. While this graph tells us nothing of the quality of these strategies, it is interesting to note that most of them show an inclination for the latter.

4 Quantifying the Relationship: Regression Analysis¶

4.1 Multiple linear regression¶

Having visualised our chosen variables and their relationship with salary, we introduce a multiple regression model to further substantiate our findings and quantify the relationships discovered. We regress salary (dependent variable) against experience, nationality and PER score (independent variables), using positions as our control variables. Since nationality and positions are categorical variables, we created dummy variables: ‘C’, ‘PF’, ‘PG’, ‘SF’ and ‘Foreign?’ where they each take the value 1 if true and 0 otherwise).

From our previous visualisation and analysis, we expect the salary of an NBA player to increase as experience and performance increase. Using the multiple linear regression model, fitted by the Least Squares Estimation (OLS) method, we hope to confirm this correlation, as well as quantify the relationship, which could also allow for future modelling if we hope to predict a player’s salary.

In [182]:
## Preparing data for regression analysis
# Creating dummy variables for categorical variables
data['Foreign?'] = 0
for i in range(len(data)):
    if data['Country'][i]=='United States':
        data.loc[i,'Foreign?'] = 0
    if data['Country'][i]!='United States':
        data.loc[i,'Foreign?'] = 1
df1_dummy = pd.get_dummies(data["Position"])
data = pd.concat([data, df1_dummy], axis=1)

data['Foreign?'] = data['Foreign?'].astype(float)
data['C'] = data['C'].astype(float)
data['PF'] = data['PF'].astype(float)
data['PG'] = data['PG'].astype(float)
data['SF'] = data['SF'].astype(float)
data['SG'] = data['SG'].astype(float)

In the summary statistics, we can easily observe the estimated regression coefficients as well as the intercept. The second output is included to suppress the scientific notation in the statistics summary. Additionally, we observe the R-squared which is 42%, which means that independent variables are “responsible” for 42% of the variation of the variable of interest that is salary. This is pretty substantial given that we have only used three explanatory variables in the model.

However, we can see that the really small p-values are those corresponding to the independent variables of experience and PER only. The corresponding correlations of these two variables with salary are statistically significant. The regression coefficient of experience is 723784.73, which actually means that an increase in one year of experience would increase the salary by \$723,784.73. In the same manner, an increase of one unit of PER would increase the salary of the player by \\$360,056.

The model outputs that the coefficient of nationality (defined as whether or not a player is foreign or not) is 316876, which would mean that on average, foreign players earned \$316,876 more than US players. However, we cannot conclude that this is always the case given that it is statistically insignificant. Instead, it could be that foreign players in our sample are paid more that season as they are inherently very skilled players who happen to be foreign. It is more plausible that NBA teams headhunt only the best players from other countries, and could be more lax with their standards for domestic players. It could also be that foreign players have a different playing style that translates to better PER statistics and hence higher salaries. There are many possibilities; we cannot however conclude that there is a correlation between salary and nationality. These findings align with our insights from our visualisation plots earlier.

4.2 Correlation tests¶

To further analyse the relationship between salary, experience and performance respectively, we introduce two well-known correlation tests, namely the Pearson’s correlation test and the Kendall’s rank correlation test. The former test is used to interpret linear relationships while the latter is used for non-linear ones.

Kendall's tau: 0.52294
p-value: 0.00000

Relationship between salary and performance
Pearsons correlation coefficient: 0.45866
p-value: 0.00000
Kendall's tau: 0.28261
p-value: 0.00000

Starting with the Pearson's correlation coefficient, we can observe that both variables are positively linearly correlated with salary, and the correlation between salary and experience is stronger (= 0.57) than the correlation between the salary and performance (=0.45). Both have very small p-values, hence we can conclude that these correlations are statistically significant. Similarly, Kendall's rank correlation test fetches positive tau values with very small p-values for both variables, implying a positive non-linear correlation with salary. This time though, Kendall’s tau value for experience (=0.52) is a lot higher than that of performance (=0.28). These outcomes signal the possibility of a non-parametric relationship between the variables which would warrant further tests and analysis. We foresee some difficulties, however, such as the limits of the data that can be collected. Experience is measured by the years of experience and basketball, as with all sports, can be age sensitive. It is difficult to find players above a certain number of years of experience simply because many of them retire due to decreased agility or simply fatigue from having played for so many years. This limits our dataset greatly, which could then hinder more accurate analysis of the relationship.

4.3 K-means clustering¶

Having quantified the relationships, we use the k-means clustering method to cluster the data into five clusters. The choice of the five clusters was made arbitrarily. We chose salary, age, experience as well as the five positions to inform our clustering algorithm. After implementing the k-means method, the algorithm assigns a number from 0 to 4 inclusive.

In [186]:
# Creating kmeans model with 5 clusters
kmeans_model = KMeans(n_clusters=5, random_state=1) 
columns = data[["Salary","C","PF","PG","SF","SG","Age","Years of experience"]]
kmeans_model.fit(columns)
labels = kmeans_model.labels_

After implementing the k-means method, we apply the Principle Component Analysis (PCA) to "summarise" the key information of all eight variables used, reducing the dimensionality of our data so as to synthesise two principal components.

In [187]:
# Two dimensions pattern recognition
pca_2 = PCA(2)
plot_columns = pca_2.fit_transform(columns)

fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
plt.scatter(x=plot_columns[:,0], y=plot_columns[:,1],c=labels)
plt.xlabel("Principal Component 1")
plt.ylabel("Principal Component 2")
plt.show()

In the above graph it is easy to distinguish the five clusters. We then look into the summary of the five clusters to recognise patterns or specific characteristics of each cluster of players.

The clustering results show us that the largest group of NBA players (250 NBA players) exist in the first cluster. All these players share some common characteristics. Specifically, they have approximately 5.5 years of experience, they are in their mid 20's, with around 11.5 performance in the league. Additionally, their mean salary is \$1,390,000 while there is an equal distribution over the positions. In the second cluster, 57 NBA players can be found. Their mean age is about 30 years old and their years of experience reaches 11, with a mean annual salary of about \\$10,980,000 (higher than the first cluster). In the second cluster, the distribution of positions is also almost uniform. The third cluster contains 28 players with approximately the same years of experience (13 years) and the same age (28 years old) as in the second cluster. The key difference between the second and third cluster is the salary and the performance of the players. Due to the fact that they are more experienced players, they were paid more than the other clusters (\$23,345,000). Additionally, the most popular position in the third cluster is the center. Finally, the fourth and fifth clusters present almost the same years of experience as well as the same age, while their mean salaries are quite different. For the fourth cluster the salary is \\$5,462,400 while the fifth is \$16,164,000. This difference can be explained by the higher performance statistics that the fifth cluster contains. While we are unable to easily distinguish the clusters from intuition and ascertain what each cluster represents, knowing that salary has such distinct clustering patterns is in itself helpful and could be the starting point of further training and analysis to better generalise each cluster’s characteristics.

5 The Evolution of Salary from 2007-2017¶

Lastly, we turn to a time series analysis including the 10 preceding so as to visualise the evolution of salaries over time. This will give us an added dimension to understand how accurate and consistent salary can truly be as an estimator/predictor of a player’s characteristics.

5.1 Data acquisition¶

For this time series analysis we decided to focus on salaries. To do so, we used the same technique as in the 2016-2017 season. For each season, we collected the links to the personal pages of each player and extracted their salary. To avoid long running times, we imported the final dataframe extracted as a CSV file for our subsequent analysis.

5.2 Trend of salary over time¶

First, we start with a simple overview of the evolution of total and average salary in each NBA season. Median salary is used as mean salary would be susceptible to biases from outliers and other measurement errors.

In [4]:
## Salary time series data
'''Salaries have been scraped in the same way for 11 seasons, 2007 to 2017.
The time series data is stored in a CSV file, which will be imported here.'''
salaries = pd.read_csv("Datasets/salaries.csv")

# Cleaning the data
salaries = salaries.astype(int)
salaries = salaries.iloc[:,1:]
salaries = salaries.replace(0,np.nan)
In [9]:
## How total and average salary changed over time

bar = []
line = []
for i in range(0,11):
    y = sum(salaries.dropna().iloc[:,i])/1000000000
    bar.append(y)
    y = median(salaries.dropna().iloc[:,i])/1000000
    line.append(y)

season = ['2007','2008','2009','2010','2011','2012','2013','2014','2015','2016',' 2017']

fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,6))
ax.bar(season, bar, color="green")
ax.set_xlabel("Year",fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel("Total salary (per billion $)",color="green",fontsize=14)

ax2=ax.twinx()
ax2.plot(season, line,color="blue",marker="o")
ax2.set_ylabel("Median salary (per million $)",color="blue",fontsize=14)

ax.set_title("Total and average salary paid out from 2007-17")
plt.show()

We hypothesise that there would be a consistent increase in salary paid out over the years due to the growth in popularity and profitability of the NBA. However, it is surprising to see that no substantial rise in total salary expenditure can be noticed before 2015. In fact, total salary expenditure even decreased between 2009 and 2011. Measurement errors seem unlikely and the cleaning process got rid of the few outliers that could have introduced biases in the data. The reasons for this discrepancy are outside the scope of this report and would necessitate further analysis.

Nonetheless, it seems evident that player salaries mirror the maximum salary cap. In fact, when the cap decreased in 2009 (-1.7%), median and total salary aIso dropped. As the salary cap stagnated in the following years, so did wages. When the cap finally increased in 2014 (+7.47%) followed by more substantial increases in 2015 (+11%), 2016 (+34.5%) and 2017 (+5.26%), salaries followed. Perhaps a larger sample of seasons would show differences in the evolution of the salary cap and of NBA salary. Nonetheless, this striking correlation is made obvious in this short time series analysis.

Lastly, while both total salary and median salary trends mirror each other, the changes in both variables are not proportional to each other. Median salary seems to have a slightly greater sensitivity and variability from year to year. Nonetheless, an increase in total salary seems to benefit all players as it usually results in an increase of median salaries for every player.

5.3 Inequality of salary over time¶

We are also interested in the change in inequality of salary distribution over the years. Distribution of salaries is visualised in multiple boxplots.

In [195]:
## How distribution of salary changed over time
seasons={}
s = [2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017]
for i in range(0,11):
    season = s[i]
    seasons[season]=salaries.iloc[:,i].dropna().apply(lambda x: x / 1000000)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,8))
ax.boxplot(seasons.values(), showfliers=False)
ax.set_ylabel('Salary (per million $)')
ax.set_xticklabels(seasons.keys())
ax.set_title("Distribution of salaries from 2007-17")
plt.show()

As we can see, the general shape of the boxplots remained constant throughout the years - a long top whisker and a short bottom whisker. The middle 50% of salaries remain relatively equal in size (no extreme variations in average salary over the years), although some years, such as 2007, 2012, 2013 and 2015, see a smaller variation. These correspond with smaller total salary expenditure in the previous bar graph, which could mean that a lower total salary leads to less variations in the average player salary. Hence, it can be hypothesised that total salary increases are pushed by star players obtaining big contracts. Indeed, this theory would reconcile increasing total salaries and increasing wage inequality.

Another exception is the distribution of salaries in 2017. It is a lot more unequal than the preceding seasons. Indeed, even though the middle 50% of salary distribution is on a relatively equal level albeit over a larger range, the maximum salary (excluding outliers) increased from 14 to 19 million dollars and the upper whisker which represents the top 25% of salaries grew longer. This indicates that a few players earned a lot more money while the rest of the league did not see a proportional increase.

In [196]:
## Joyplot of salaries over time
joyplot(salaries/1000000, colormap=cm.autumn_r, kind='kde', fade=True, range_style='own', tails=0.2,
        background='w', figsize = (10,6), title = 'Distribution of Annual Salary Earned per NBA Player from 2007-2017')
plt.axvline(x=0, color='blue', ls='--')
plt.show()

We see this inequality clearly in the above ridgeline plot as well. The longer and thicker tail of the 2017 season, as well as the lower maximum peak of the density plot, supports the above conclusion that wage inequality grew in 2017. In this plot, it is clearer which seasons see greater inequality in their salary distribution as it allows us to see the distribution without being categorised into quantiles like in the box plot. Seasons with a shorter right tail such as 2010 and 2015 see a less unequal salary distribution. This is a useful added dimension as from the previous box plot, the distribution of salary in 2009 and 2010 seems similar. However, the density plots reveal a slight decrease in inequality in 2010. Overall, there does not seem to be a consistent trend of improving or worsening inequality in salary distribution; it varies from season to season, though it is clear that the NBA salary distribution has always been highly unequal in nature.

6 Conclusion¶

This report set out to find the hidden secret determinants of NBA salaries and what they could tell us about professional basketball players. The determinants of the salaries of professional sports players has always been a mystery. It was thus very insightful to search for the formula of an NBA player’s salary.

Our first finding is how unequally distributed salaries in the NBA are. This pushed us to explore the determinants of salary. Straight away, performance and experience stood out as an important determinant of wage. Later, regression analysis would confirm this intuition as a clear correlation between salary and these two variables was established. Then, we explored possible wage variations based on country of origin though despite an overwhelming representation of American players in the league, we were unable to conclude that there is discrimination based on nationality. Furthermore, potential wage discrepancies between positions did not return conclusive correlation, which is commendable as every position on the team is equally important in the team’s performance in a game. Lastly, the time series analysis unveiled the evolution of total salary expenditure and average salaries between 2007 and 2017. In particular, the increase of total salary expenditure closely mirrored the fluctuations of the salary cap showing how particular wage policies, such as the salary cap, can shape labour markets.

Some themes briefly mentioned in this report could be explored in more depth. For one, the growth of international representation is one that we are particularly interested in. Indeed, the growing popularity of basketball outside of the US has opened up the league to a vast new pool of talents. New data science techniques could be applied to model and predict the evolution of foreign players in the sport and their impact on the league. How will the proportion of foreign players change in the coming years? Will the NBA be able to remain attractive to these foreign talents? How will the league’s marketing strategies evolve to reach an ever growing foreign fan base?
